reatening a raid in the near future\nGedar posts for sale by G E\nBroaddusHopkinsville Ky Cum\nberland phone No 838\nThe kindyour grandfather used\nand he was of rare judgment Profit\nby his experience and use Old 1 W\nHarper whiskey Sold by W R\nLong Hopkinsville Ky\nCall at this office for ham sacks\ntwo sizes\nUndisguised night riders called\nPaul Kautz of Berlin Bracken coun\ntyfrom hishome but wete persuade\ned not to whip him after he had\npromised to buy no more tobacco\nCedar posts for sale by G E\nBroaddus Hopkinsville Ky Cum\nberland phone No 838\nCorsby S Noyes editor of the\nen\nWashington Star died Friday ar\nPasadena Cal aged 83 years\nCedar posts for sale by G E\nBroaddus Hopkinsville Ky Cum\nberland phone No 838\nMadisonville is to have a canning\nfactory\nList your real estate for sale with\nJ F ELLIS\nMULES FOR SALE\nWe have 50 head of\ngood mules for sale\nLayne Leavel\nHopkinsville Ky\nI Cottage For Rent\n1 Fiveroom cottage new and in ex\ncellent repair at 28 West IJth street\nPossession this week\nCHAS MMBACHAM\nBig Sum For Education\nThe bill appropriating 200000\nto Kentucky State College and 150\n000 to each of the Normal school\nwas passed by the lower house Fri\nday after a long debate Amend\nmints reducing the size of the ap\npropriation were rejected\nA\nHouse For Rent\nFive room house on Walnut ftreel\nl Immediate possession\nr JF ELLIS\nJ\nASSOCIATION\nASSOCIATIONiEETINB\nr\nApplications For Membership\nReported By\nt Several\nHALF CROP MARKETED\nIf\nWard Headly Spoke In The\nAfternoon To a Large\nCrowd\nI\nFourteen or fifteen of the county\nexecutive committee of the tobacco\nassociation met in the county court\nroom yesterday VicePresident W\nT Fowler presided The President\nW W Radford telephoned to Judge\nFowler that he would not be able to\nbe present on the account of the ill\nI ness of his wife\nReports from the committeemen\npresent showed that approximately\nhalf of the 1907 crop had been deliv\nI\nI ered to die association warehouses\nReports showed that none of the\nmembers of tha association had sold\ntheir crops out of the association\nTwo reported having bought share\nhands interests in crops and putting\nit in with their own tobacco which\nwas approved by the committee\nThe schedule for the 1908 crop\nseems to be meeting with general\napproval This schedule permits a\nfarmer to plant 7 acres of the first\n100 acres and 2i for each additional\n50 acres\nacresQuite a number of planters have\nsigned a petition for membership\nunder the plan adopted last Monday\nOne committeeman reported that he\nhad taken the signatures of 30 ap\nplicants and another reported 12 ap\nplications The new plan adopted\nfor getting all tobacco growers into\nthe association is popular and it is\nthought by the time the books of\nthe association are opened the first\nof May practically every tobacco I\ngrower in the county will belong to\nthe association\nassociationMr\nMr J W Foard reported to the\ncommittee that he had cultivated an\nacre of tobacco last year in order to\nascertain what kind of tobacco is\nbest adapted to our soil The crop\nwas planted and cultivated for thc\nAgricultural Department at Wash\nington About twentyfour varie\nties were experimented with and\nMr Foard gave it as his opinion that\nMadole is best for this climate\nand soil The acre of tobacco was\nput into one lot and sold for 9725\nthed\nlarge gathering of farmers and\nothers that the association has a\ngrievance committee composed\nof S G Buckner Frank s\nand W A Glass who are to hear\nminor grievances that have hereto\nfore been brought before the execut\nive committee Adjourned to meet\ni again next Monday\nBeforethe vote for adjournmen\nwas taken Dennis Perry announced\nthat owing to a previous engage\nments Mr Joel Fort was unable t\nbe here and address the committee\nMr Ward Headley of Princeton\nwas announced to speak at 130\nRings Little Liver Pills wake ai\nlazy livers clean the system and\nclear the skin Try them for bilious\nness and sick headache Price 25c\nSold by AndersonFowler Drug CO1\nincorporated\nDeserves Attentive Hearing\nThe earnest appeal of the Law and\nOrder League of Hdpkinsville and\nChristian county deserves an atten\ntive hearing from the General As\nsembly Its recital of the outrage\nperpetrated in Christian count y\nshould move any conscience More\nover it should convince the skepti\ncal that it is not true that the resi\ndents in the mobridden districts de\nsire inaction by the Legislature ThE\nmembers of the league merit thE\nI hearty commendation of all patrioti\nKentuckians Their example migh\nI be followed advantageously mother\ncounties whose people are kept in IJ\nstate of terror by the menace of thE\nnight riders CourierJournal\nridersCourierJournalWanted\nWanted\nTo make shirt waists skirts and\nchildrens clothes and also comfort\nand quilts MRS C E HORD\n917 East Seventh Stv\nTHEY AREy ON THEIR WAY\nWe will have them in Shoes and Oxfords Pat Tan Gun Metal and plain xVioi All\nwIdths and sizes\nThis is the first time this line has ever been handled by a retail store We are exclusive\nagents Call ands e them before buying v\nWarfield West Shoe Company\nINCORPORATED\nIPoints About People\nMis Lucy Dade is visiting in India\nnapolis Ind i\nMrs Nick Gaither of Louisville\narrived Saturday on a short visit\nto her parents Mr and Mrs Walter\nKelly V\nMessrs Henry M ind Sam Frank\nel have gone to New Y rkto buy\nspring goods\nE Tanner fa in New York\nMr and Mrs WalterBarned have\ntaken rooms and board at Mr\nQuicksMiss\nI Miss Mary West a student at Bel\nmont College Nashville is spending\nthe week at home\nMisses Virginia Tibbs and Annie\nCox spent Saturday with the family\nof Mr Cloud in the courtry\nM E Bacon has rented and\nmoved into the residence of Walter\nHarned on East Ninth street\nT B Mason and family who\nmoved to Texas last fall have re\nturned to this city i\nMisses Fannie and Npra Rogers\nleft yesterday for the eastern mar\nkets to buy spring millinery\nI\nRodman Meacham has returned\nfrom Jonesboro Tenn after an ab\nsence of six months on business I\ni\nMrs W A Evans left yesterday\non a visit to the family of her father\nMr J R Plummer at NewportKy\nAttorney General James Breathitt\ncame down from Frankfort Satur\nday and will remain until Hedhes\nday He hepes to be able to com\nplete arrangements for taking his\nfamily with him when he returns to\nthe State capital\nSenator Frank Rives spent Satur\nday and Sunday in the city the leg\nislature having adjourned over Sat\nurday it being the anniversary of\nWashingtons birthday\nBeale Smith of Memphis spent\nSunday with his mbther Mrs D W\nKitchen\nMr and Mrs R L Jackson and\nthet\nfromd\nl Nashville\nCapt John C Dabney Jno W\nKelly W R Shaw Hobt Crenshaw\nand M D Keats of Cadiz were all\nin town yesterday at the opening of\ncourtCommonwealths\nCommonwealths Attorney Smith\nI is in the city to attend to Circuit\nCourt matters\nMiss Annie McPherson went to\nLouisville yesterday for a visit to\nrelatives\nBIG PREPARATIONS\nI\nFor Services at the Christian\nChurch Sunday\ns t\nWe understand that all prelimina\nries have about been perfected for\nformally reopening the enlarged au\nditorium of the Christian church\nnext Sunday The full program\nhowever has not yet been furnished\nfor publication but will be in a few\ndays In additipn to the program\nof the morning there will be an af\nternoon service at which the an\nnual rollcall will be made\nMtco Levis to Wee\nI4 Awl vv v 3\nRev and Mrs John W Lewis of\nthis city announce the engagement\nI 6f their daughter May Roberts\nI Lewis to Mr Harvey A Dunlap of\nSt Louis The wedding will take\nplace early in June\nNEGROES WHIPPED\nThe Citizens of Madisonville\nStruggl for Places to See\nWhipping Executed\nMadisonville Ky Feb 24nThe\nfirst public whipping that ever took\nplace in Madisonville was pulled off\nin the courthouse yard Saturday\nmorning when jailer Craig adminis\ntered fifteen licks each to five young\nnegroes in the presence of about\nfour hundred citizens\nThe negroes whipped were Gar\nland Goodloe Ben Cook Jack Por\nter Alex Majors and Thomas Rake\nstraw boys ranging in age from 12\nto 18 A few weeks ago a gang of\nthieves were operating in the city\nbreaking into almost every business\nhouse in town and the police finally\ncaptured one of the boys whipped\nwho gave the namespf his compan\nions and they confessed to all of the\ncrimes In the Circuit Court they\nwere sentenced to the penitentiary\nbut on account of their youth Judge\nGordon suspended the sentences\nprovided the parents of the boys\nwere willing that they be whipped\npublicly This was consented to by\nthe parents of five of the boys the\nsixth being unwilling that their son\nbe punished in such a manner and he\nwill go to the penitentiary I\nA barrel was placed in the court\nhouse yard staked down and the\nboys were laid across this one at a\ntime and the Jailer applied the lash\nacross their backs That he put it\non strong was quite evident for the\nnegroes let out yells that could be\nheard for quite a distance and it\nwas hard to keep them across the\nbarrel The courthouse yard was\nfull of people and many climbed\ntelephone poles windows were occu\npied and many were on sheds in\nfront of stores\nPennyrile Pencil Pushers\nPaducah Ky Feb 22iThe Pen\nnyrile Press Association composed\nof newspaper men of Western Ken\ntucky met here and elected officers\nas follows\nasfollowsPresident\nPresident E Barry of Benton\nvice president John J Berry of Pa\nducah secretarytreasurer John L\nLawrence of Cadiz President Bar\nry appointed the following Execu\ntive Committee J K Lemon John\nL Lawrence and W 0 Wear\nFor Sale\nSeveral fresh Jarsey Cows two of\nthem extra fine ones Phone 2084\nFulton Man Defiant\nFultort Ky Feb 22 Thomas\nHamlet will not leave Fulton in\nspite of the warnings of tho night\nriders and guards surround his\nproperties armed with enough pow\nder andball to blow all the riders\ni Kentucky into the Mississippi\nGov Willson has shipped enough\narms here to resist a siegemuch less\na night attack and Hamlet is having\nhis barns carefully patrolled\nFor Sale at a Bargain\nScholarship in ono of the best Bus Y\niness Universaties of the South\nGood for any department Address\nthis office\nCockerels\nPlymouth Rock Cockerels for sale\nat prices ranging from 150 to 300\nOnly a few left\nRALPH MEACHAM\nPhones 94 and 1122\nr i\nHam racks for saleat thisoffjce\nJ\nMR BRYANS OPINIONS\nThe plan of guaranteed bank de\nposits has probably found favor\namong all classes of people and irre\nspective of political affliation more\nrapidly than any other public ques\ntion\nThe new state of Oklahoma has\nalready enacted law taxing state\nbanks the fund thus accumulated tq\nbe used in paying the depositors of\nany state bank that from any cause\nbecomes Unable to meet its obliga\ntions A special session of the Kan\nsas legislature has been called for\nthe purpose of enacting legislation\nsimilar to the Oklahoma plan The\ngovernor of Nebraska is considering\nthe advisability of calling a special\nsession of the legislature on account\nof the growing belief among the peo\npIe that protection to bank deposi\ntors in the form of state or federal\nguarantees of their deposits will stop\nthe hoarding of money bring into\ncirculation sufficient currency to con\nduct the business of the country and\nprevent a recurrence of such dis\nastrous panics as the one through\nwhich we are now passing\nMr Bryan has been an advocate\nof a law guaranteeing deposits in\nstate and national banks since 1893\nMr Bryan in discussing the tariff\nquestions insists that residents of the\nI United States should be permitted\nw\nSEEDo\ni\nWe have a nice line ofi\nFIELD SEED OF ALL KINDS\nBOOSTS ADVERTISING\nGov WLDouglas Increases\nBusiness\nWashington Feb22 As an instance\nof the value of newspaper advertis\ning to increase or force trade the\nfollowing facts are remarkable Dur\ning December the orders received\nby the Douglas Boot and Shoe Com\npany of Brockton Mass fell off in\nconsequence of the business depres\nsion following the panic The ad\nvertising manager of that large con\ncern mentioned the matter to Gov\nDouglas and asked his advice\nwhether under the circumstances\nthey should place the usual amount\nof advertising during January and\nFebruary which are usually the\nslowest months in the yearin the\nshoe business Gov Douglas at\nonce ordered an increase of 3Q per\ncent in the amount appropriated\nfor advertising declaring that such\nan increase would help to overcome\nthe unfavorable business outlook\nThere was considerable skepticism\nabout the matter among the princi\npjU employes of the Douglas Corn\npany But the result showed almost I\nan immediate improvement in busi\nness which is nQw averaging more\nthan last year during these usually\ndull months\nThusthe business sagacity pf Gov i\nDouglas has overcome the hard\nI\nI times and his optimism has proven\nto buy homemade goods at home at\nas low a price as the foreigner can\nbuy Americanmade goods abroad\nHe also insists that bur government\nshould be by and for the people as\na whole rather than by and for the\ntrusts and administered in the in\nterest of a few beneficiaries of the\ntrust system He believes that na\ntional legislation for the purpose of\nbetter regulation and control of in\nterstate commerce and common car\nriers should supplement state legis\nlation and not be n substitute for\nstate legislation\nMrBryans paperThe Commoner\nreflects his opinions each week on\nquestions of public importance and\nin its columns may also be found\nhis magazine articles public speech\nes addresses and lectures which\nare referred to in the daily press\nfrom day to day\nIf you are interested in political\nquestions if you desire to keep in\ntouchwith the progress of the cam\npaign and to read Mr Bryans cam\npaign speeches send sixty cents to\nThe Commoner and the paper will\nbe sent to you each week until the\nclose of the next presidential cam\npaign\nPostoffice money order currency\nor stamps will be accepted Only\nsixty cents Address The Commoner\nLincoln Neb\nf\nJail and let us show you through or phone\nus your wants\nj\nMONARCH GRAIN Co\nINCORPORATED\nan antidote to the panic\nThe advertising manager of Gov\nDouglas explains the phenomenon\nof increased sales when by all the\nrules of business there should have\nbeen a decrease as entirely produc N\ned by the increased advertising\nOther advertisers of shoes were\ndrawing in their horns and many of\ntheir former customers were induced\nto patronize the Douglas shoe be\ncause it was more than ever brought\nto their notice\nIt seems that persistent advertis\ning pays for last year nearly 8000\nnewspapers carried the Douglas ad\nvertisement and the profits of the\nbusiness were larger than ever The\nbusiness i managers of newspapers\nshouldtpoint out these facts to those\nwho Decrease or decline tp adver\ntise at all when business is drooping\nand show them that PJi\nvertisihg pays and that increased i\nvertising pays better and that the\nnewspaper is the best advertising\nmediumFeudists\nFeudists Fearful Fate\nLouisa Ky Feb 22 Whether\nor not it was the McCoys who caught\nThomas Hatfield alone Trigg river\nin West Virginia or not he died\nhere today of exposure\nHo had been bound to a tree on r\nthe river bank and left to freeze\nToes and fingers were frozen off\nand he was brought here almost\ndead\nJ r\n1\n4 I\nti dIf I\nJf t tt 1 fI r 1111 JII ijr 0 I\nf tr irc iri f tI\nr 1\na\ni\ni\niiI f\nJ\nf\n1\nI i\nj\nI t\nI\n1 t\nM\nJ\n1\nj\nj\n4j\n1 i\nt\n3\nf\ny\nt yh\ni\nII\ntI\ntI\nI\nII\nr\nkii\n1\ni\noi","height":"30816","width":"21360"}}
